**Solution Explanation**

For a set of points in the plane the *maximum possible distance* between two of them is called the **diameter** of the set.  
A well‑known way to find the diameter is:

1. **Convex Hull** – the farthest pair of points must lie on the convex hull of the set.  
   We build the hull with the monotone chain algorithm (O(n log n)).

2. **Rotating Calipers** – once the hull is known we can find the farthest pair in linear time (O(m), where m is the hull size).  
   While walking around the hull we keep a second pointer that always points to the vertex that gives the largest area of the parallelogram formed by the current edge and the line to that vertex.  
   The distance between the two pointers is a candidate for the diameter.

The algorithm works for all input sizes, handles collinear points correctly and uses only integer arithmetic until the final square‑root.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Algorithm
```
read n
read all points

if n <= 1
    answer = 0
else
    // 1. Build convex hull
    sort points by (x, y)
    build lower hull
    build upper hull
    hull = lower + upper (without duplicate endpoints)

    // 2. Rotating calipers
    m = hull.size()
    if m == 2
        answer = distance(hull[0], hull[1])
    else
        j = 1
        maxDistSq = 0
        for i = 0 … m-1
            next = (i+1) mod m
            // move j while area increases
            while area(hull[i], hull[next], hull[(j+1) mod m]) >
                  area(hull[i], hull[next], hull[j])
                j = (j+1) mod m
            // update maximum distance
            maxDistSq = max(maxDistSq,
                            distSq(hull[i], hull[j]),
                            distSq(hull[next], hull[j]))
        answer = sqrt(maxDistSq)

output "Final Answer: " + answer with 6 digits after decimal point
```

*`distSq(a,b)`* – squared Euclidean distance (long long).  
*`area(a,b,c)`* – absolute value of cross product of vectors **ab** and **ac** (long long).  
All intermediate values fit into 64‑bit signed integers because coordinates are integers and the cross product of two vectors with coordinates up to 10⁹ is at most 10¹⁸.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Correctness Proof  

We prove that the algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between any two points.

---

##### Lemma 1  
For any set of points in the plane, the farthest pair of points lies on the convex hull of the set.

**Proof.**  
Assume a farthest pair `p, q` is not on the hull.  
Then at least one of them lies inside the convex hull.  
The convex hull is the smallest convex set containing all points, so the segment `pq` lies entirely inside the hull.  
Any point of the hull is at least as far from the other point as `p` or `q` (by convexity), contradicting the maximality of `pq`. ∎



##### Lemma 2  
During the rotating calipers loop, for each edge `h[i]h[next]` the pointer `j` is the vertex that maximizes the area of the parallelogram formed by this edge and the line to `h[j]`.

**Proof.**  
The algorithm starts with `j = 1`.  
For a fixed edge `h[i]h[next]` the area function is unimodal as we walk around the hull: it increases until the farthest point from the line, then decreases.  
The while‑condition moves `j` forward as long as the area increases, therefore after the loop terminates `j` is at a local maximum.  
Because the hull is convex, this local maximum is the global maximum for that edge. ∎



##### Lemma 3  
For every edge of the convex hull, the algorithm checks the distance between the two vertices that can be farthest apart with respect to that edge.

**Proof.**  
By Lemma&nbsp;2, after the while‑loop `j` is the vertex that maximizes the area for the current edge.  
For a convex polygon the farthest pair of vertices that are “opposite” to a given edge must be among the vertices that maximize this area.  
The algorithm evaluates the distances `h[i]–h[j]` and `h[next]–h[j]`, which are the only candidates that can be farthest for this edge. ∎



##### Lemma 4  
The maximum squared distance found by the algorithm equals the squared diameter of the convex hull.

**Proof.**  
By Lemma&nbsp;3, for each edge the algorithm considers all pairs that could be the farthest with respect to that edge.  
The farthest pair of the whole hull must be farthest with respect to some edge (take the edge of the hull that is incident to one of the two points).  
Thus the algorithm will evaluate that pair and its squared distance will be stored in `maxDistSq`.  
No larger distance can exist, so `maxDistSq` equals the squared diameter. ∎



##### Theorem  
The algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between any two points of the input set.

**Proof.**  
By Lemma&nbsp;1 the farthest pair lies on the convex hull.  
By Lemma&nbsp;4 the algorithm finds the squared diameter of the hull.  
Taking the square root gives the Euclidean distance, which is printed.  
Therefore the printed value is exactly the maximum possible distance. ∎



--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Complexity Analysis

Let `n` be the number of input points and `m` the number of hull vertices (`m ≤ n`).

*Sorting* – `O(n log n)`  
*Hull construction* – `O(n)`  
*Rotating calipers* – `O(m)`  

Total time complexity: **O(n log n)**  
Memory usage: the points and hull – **O(n)**

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### Reference Implementation  (C++17)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Point {
    long long x, y;
    bool operator<(const Point& other) const {
        if (x != other.x) return x < other.x;
        return y < other.y;
    }
};

long long cross(const Point& O, const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    return (A.x - O.x) * (B.y - O.y) - (A.y - O.y) * (B.x - O.x);
}

long long distSq(const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    long long dx = A.x - B.x;
    long long dy = A.y - B.y;
    return dx * dx + dy * dy;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    if (!(cin >> n)) return 0;
    vector<Point> pts(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) cin >> pts[i].x >> pts[i].y;

    if (n <= 1) {
        cout << "Final Answer: 0.000000\n";
        return 0;
    }

    sort(pts.begin(), pts.end());

    // Build lower hull
    vector<Point> lower;
    for (const auto& p : pts) {
        while (lower.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(lower[lower.size()-2], lower.back(), p) <= 0)
            lower.pop_back();
        lower.push_back(p);
    }
    // Build upper hull
    vector<Point> upper;
    for (int i = n-1; i >= 0; --i) {
        const auto& p = pts[i];
        while (upper.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(upper[upper.size()-2], upper.back(), p) <= 0)
            upper.pop_back();
        upper.push_back(p);
    }

    // Concatenate, removing duplicate endpoints
    lower.pop_back();
    upper.pop_back();
    vector<Point> hull = lower;
    hull.insert(hull.end(), upper.begin(), upper.end());
    int m = hull.size();

    long long maxDistSq = 0;
    if (m == 2) {
        maxDistSq = distSq(hull[0], hull[1]);
    } else {
        int j = 1;
        for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
            int ni = (i + 1) % m;
            // Move j while area increases
            while (abs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[(j + 1) % m])) >
                   abs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[j])))
                j = (j + 1) % m;
            maxDistSq = max(maxDistSq, distSq(hull[i], hull[j]));
            maxDistSq = max(maxDistSq, distSq(hull[ni], hull[j]));
        }
    }

    double answer = sqrt((double)maxDistSq);
    cout << "Final Answer: " << fixed << setprecision(6) << answer << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

The program follows exactly the algorithm proven correct above and conforms to the required output format.

